{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583988"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:34:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:34:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14209"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14209"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6895"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104070"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6895"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14209"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86388"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5327"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12733"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32924"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39982"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104070"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old Aboriginal woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. She has a history of type 2 diabetes and depression. During the consultation, she mentions that her grandmother was forcibly removed from her family as a child and placed in a mission. The patient expresses feelings of disconnection from her culture and difficulty trusting healthcare providers. She has no other significant medical history and takes metformin and sertraline regularly.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the long-term impact of the Stolen Generations on Indigenous Australian health?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enhanced cultural integration","Increased life expectancy","Intergenerational trauma and poorer health outcomes","Reduced rates of chronic disease","Improved access to Western healthcare"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Stolen Generations refer to Indigenous Australian children who were forcibly removed from their families and communities as a result of various government policies from the late 1800s until the 1970s. This historical trauma has had profound and lasting effects on Indigenous Australian health and wellbeing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntergenerational trauma and poorer health outcomes\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer. The forced removal of children from their families has resulted in long-lasting psychological and emotional trauma that has been passed down through generations. This intergenerational trauma contributes to higher rates of mental health issues, substance abuse, and chronic diseases among Indigenous Australians. The patient\u0027s own history of depression and her expressed feelings of disconnection from her culture are examples of how this trauma can manifest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImproved access to Western healthcare\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While the stated aim of some removal policies was to provide better access to education and healthcare, the reality is that these policies have often led to distrust of mainstream services, including healthcare, among Indigenous people. This distrust can result in reduced engagement with health services and poorer health outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced rates of chronic disease\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. In fact, Indigenous Australians experience higher rates of chronic diseases such as diabetes, cardiovascular disease, and kidney disease compared to non-Indigenous Australians. The trauma and disruption caused by the Stolen Generations have contributed to these health disparities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced cultural integration\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The Stolen Generations policies led to a significant loss of cultural identity, language, and connection to land for many Indigenous people. This loss of cultural connection has had negative impacts on mental health and overall wellbeing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased life expectancy\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Indigenous Australians continue to have a lower life expectancy compared to non-Indigenous Australians, with the gap currently estimated at about 8 years. The trauma and disruption caused by the Stolen Generations have contributed to this ongoing health disparity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the historical context of the Stolen Generations and its ongoing impact is crucial for healthcare providers. It allows for a more culturally safe and trauma-informed approach to care, which can help build trust and improve health outcomes for Indigenous patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Stolen Generations have led to intergenerational trauma, contributing to poorer health outcomes for Indigenous Australians.","Forced removal policies have resulted in loss of cultural identity, language, and connection to land for many Indigenous people.","Understanding the historical context of the Stolen Generations is crucial for providing culturally safe healthcare to Indigenous Australians."],"references":["Verbunt E, Luke J, Paradies Y, Bamblett M, Salamone C, Jones A, Kelaher M. Cultural determinants of health for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people\u2013a narrative overview of reviews. International Journal for Equity in Health. 2021 Dec;20:1-9."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86388"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14209"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86388"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-29T11:04:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-29T11:04:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6895"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104070"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1196","links":{"self